# Rust 1.75 Cursor Rules

## Ownership & Borrowing
- Prefer borrowing (`&T`) over transferring ownership when possible
- Use `Clone` sparingly — it's explicit and has performance cost
- Prefer `&str` over `String` in function parameters
- Use lifetimes only when the compiler can't infer them

## Error Handling
- Use `Result<T, E>` for recoverable errors, `panic!` only for bugs
- Use `thiserror` for library error types
- Use `anyhow` for application-level error handling
- Use `?` operator for error propagation
- Implement `Display` and `Error` for custom error types

## Async (Tokio)
- Use `tokio` runtime for async I/O
- Use `async fn` and `.await` for async operations
- Use `tokio::spawn` for concurrent tasks
- Use `tokio::select!` for racing multiple futures
- Avoid blocking the async runtime — use `tokio::task::spawn_blocking`

## Code Style
- Use `rustfmt` for formatting, `clippy` for linting
- Prefer iterators over loops: `.map()`, `.filter()`, `.collect()`
- Use `match` exhaustively — handle all variants
- Use `impl Trait` for simple return types
- Prefer `From/Into` traits for type conversion over manual conversion

## Performance
- Rust is fast by default — profile before micro-optimizing
- Use `Vec` capacity hints when size is known
- Use `Cow<str>` for flexible string handling
- Use zero-copy parsing when possible
- Benchmark with `criterion` crate
